Style Sheets 
using the inline styling methods is great for applying just a couple of styling rules but does 
not work for larger collection rules. To counter this problem, reacti native uses a 
Stylesheet API.
So how do we use a style sheet?
well according to the react naative website: https://reactnative.dev/docs/stylesheet
const styles = Stylesheet.create({
  container: {
    flex: 1,
    padding: 24,
    backgroundColor: '#eaeaea'
  },
  title: {
    marginTop: 16,
    paddingVertical: 8,
    borderWidth: 4,
    borderColor: '#20232a',
    borderRadius: 6,
    backgroundColor: '#61dafb',
    color: '#20232a',
    textAlign: 'center',
    fontSize: 30,
    fontWeight: 'bold',
  },
});

what does exporting do? 
Export allows other files to import and use code (like functions, objects, or components)
from your file. By convention, export statements usually go at the end of the document.
here is an exmaple:
export const styles = StyleSheet.create({ ... });  // Export styles

// In another file:
import { styles } from './App';  // Import the exported styles

What is an API? 
An API (Applicaiton Programming Interface) is a way for apps to talk to each other and share data.
With an API you do not have to recreate the wheel again and again, but instead you can use
work that someone has already made and utilize it, such as a weather API and a notificaiton API.

So basically, when you use export const styles, you're making your styles available for 
other files to grab and use. But here's the thing—you don't actually need to export styles 
if you're only using them in the same file. The course makes you export because their tests
are in a different file and need to check if you actually created the styles. The big
difference between JavaScript and Python is how they actually read your code. Python goes
line by line from top to bottom, so if you try to use something before you define it, you
get an error. JavaScript is different though—it reads your whole file first before it 
actually runs anything. This means you can use styles.layout in your component even though 
you defined styles way down at the bottom of the file. When JavaScript loads your code, it 
scans everything first and says "okay, there's an App component, there's a styles object," 
and then when React actually renders your component, the styles are already there and ready
to use. So the order doesn't really matter like it does in Python. That's why your code works
even though technically the styles come after you're using them.
